issue.body: I'm new to Flutter/Dart and was trying to configure it to preserve trailing commas. This is nicely documented [here](https://github.com/dart-lang/dart_style/wiki/Configuration#preserve-trailing-commas) but I only found that after asking @DanTup in Discord. It's not discoverable from VSCode, Google search and coding agent didn't find it, and search [here](https://dart.dev/search?q=trailing) also didn't find it. This ticket is a feature request to add some hover info in `analysis_options.yaml` (and probably similarly for `pubspec.yaml` would be great) that has a link to the right docs page to make it possible to discover the available options. As an example of what I mean, here's what I see if I open a Python project `pyproject.toml` - a clickable link to the docs where all the options are listed. Would be great if we had that on hover over "formatter or "linter" in `analysis_options.yaml`.

comment.body:
> > I think that this issue is requesting a way to see what not-yet-included options could be added to the file.
>
> I did miss this bit.. I originally thought the request was just for hovering over the existing keys to know what they had ...

Yeah, I think this request is about making the functionality available through these files more discoverable. Having a CodeLens to get to the documentation would help, but we need to ask whether there's a better solution (that would obviate the need for a CodeLens) and/or whether there's some additional support that would work _with_ a CodeLens to make it even more discoverable.

That's part of what made me think about the lints. A link to the documentation about what lints are supported would be good, but would be inconsistent with documentation of the form "Here's a list of the options you can nest under this key." On the other hand, listing all the lints in a single hover is not practical.

> > How do we get information to display related to plugins?
>
> If you mean when you hover over a plugin name, is there a description and URL in the metadata for a plugin? (or can we infer them from the package name?).

Sorry, my question was very terse. I was thinking fairly broadly that we should have a goal to make it possible for plugins to have a first-class UX. Anything we can show in the hovers for our own lints plugin authors should be able to supply for their lints. That potentially covers a lot of things.

- If we were to have a CodeLens to open documentation about the analysis options file, then plugins ought to be able to provide a URL to open documentation about the plugin's options and we ought to have a CodeLens above the plugin name to open that page.
- If we display docs when the cursor hovers over a lint name, then plugins ought to be able to provide documentation to display for their own lints.
- If we display docs while hovering over keys, then plugins should be able to provide docs for any keys they introduce.
- And given that we support code completion in these files, plugins ought to be able to contribute enough information that we can build a `MapProducer` that allows us to complete their values.

I don't know what that API would look like or whether we have anything on our roadmap to add such support for the initial version, but we should keep it in mind when designing this feature.

issue.title: [ENH] Centralize parallel backend selection in skbase and introduce typed config class
issue.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**

There is no parallel backend API in skbase today, while sktime, skpro, and Hyperactive each carry their own backend selection and configuration using the pair backend and backend_params. 

**Describe the solution you'd like**

I propose to add a small skbase.parallel module that defines a common interface for parallel execution. Once skbase provides this shared primitive, downstream projects can remove duplicate code and depend on the central API. This is a rough sketch how those classes could look like:

```python
class LokyParallel:
    n_jobs: Optional[int] = None
    prefer: Optional[str] = None 
    require: Optional[str] = None 

class RayParallel:
    ray_remote_args: Optional[Dict[str, Any]] = None
    shutdown_ray: bool = True
    logger_name: str = "ray"
    mute_warnings: bool = False

class DaskParallel:
    scheduler: Optional[str] = None 
```

**Describe alternatives you've considered**

A nested dictionary with a single top level key was considered instead of a dataclass because it encodes the dependency in one parameter. This is harder to explain and invites deep untyped structures, which burden documentation and error messages.

comment.body:
I really like this idea!

I have some questions about the design, to be resolved we implement.

Regarding the plan, I would carry this out in two stages:

1. add the "backends" framework in `scikit-base`
2. point the "backends" framework in `sktime`, `skpro`, `hyperactive` to `scikit-base`
3. add the dataclass / config class based interface, as an alternative means to configure

CodSpeed is a **continuous benchmarking** platform that allows you to **track** and **compare** the **performance** of your codebase during development.

It uses a smart **runtime engine** to measure the performance of your code in an **accurate** and **reproducible** way without creating a huge **runtime overhead**, unlike traditional benchmarks.

CodSpeed produces detailed **performance reports** helping you **improve** your codebase **performance**, directly **within your repository provider** (Pull Requests comments, Merge checks, ...).

## How it works

The core of the **performance measurement** is done directly within your **CI environment** through the **CodSpeed Action**. Allowing you to **stay the sole owner** of your data and to keep your **codebase private**.

Once the performance data is generated, **only the benchmark results** are sent to the CodSpeed servers to be **analyzed**.

Then, performance reports are **generated** and **published** directly **within your repository provider**.

## How long does it take to install?

If you're **already benchmarking** your codebase, you can plug your **existing benchmarks** to CodSpeed in **less than 5 minutes** since CodSpeed benchmark's API is **compatible** with the most **popular benchmarking frameworks**.

If **you haven't any benchmarks yet**, we provide an **intuitive** benchmarking API that allows you to **create your first benchmarks** in a **few minutes**.

pull_request.title: Create .NET 8 Fluent Garmin Library with FIT SDK Integration and Enhanced Repeat Structure Support
pull_request.body:
This PR implements a complete .NET 8 library that provides a fluent wrapper around Garmin's FIT SDK for creating workout files with proper repeat structure support. The library enables developers to easily generate Garmin-compatible workout files using an intuitive, builder-pattern API that follows Garmin's recommended patterns for intervals.

## Key Features

**Fluent API Design**: The library provides an easy-to-use builder pattern for creating workouts with comprehensive examples:

```csharp
// Basic workout pattern
var workout = new WorkoutBuilder()
    .Name("Morning Run")
    .Sport(Sport.Running)
    .WarmUp(10, 1, TargetType.HeartRate)
    .AddTimeStep("Main Set", 20, 4, TargetType.HeartRate)
    .CoolDown(5, 1, TargetType.HeartRate)
    .Build();

// Interval workout with repeat structure using option objects
var intervalOptions = new IntervalOptions 
{
    DurationType = DurationType.Distance,
    Value = 400,
    Zone = 4,
    TargetType = TargetType.Speed
};

var recoveryOptions = new RecoveryOptions
{
    DurationType = DurationType.Time,
    Value = 120,
    TargetType = TargetType.Open
};

var intervals = new WorkoutBuilder()
    .Name("Track Intervals")
    .Sport(Sport.Running)
    .WarmUp(10, 1)
    .AddIntervals("5x400m", 5, intervalOptions, recoveryOptions)
    .CoolDown(10, 1)
    .Build();
```

**Enhanced Method Naming**: Clear distinction between different types of workout steps:
- `AddTimeStep()` and `AddDistanceStep()` for individual workout segments (easy runs, tempo efforts, etc.)
- `AddIntervals()` for structured interval training with repeat patterns
- `AddRepeat()` for custom repeat structures with child steps

**Explicit Parameter Structure**: The `AddIntervals()` method requires explicit option objects for improved code clarity:
- Uses `IntervalOptions` and `RecoveryOptions` parameter objects that must be created and passed in
- Removes convenience overloads that built options internally for better API explicitness

**Proper Repeat Structure Support**: Uses Garmin's FIT SDK repeat patterns instead of manually creating individual steps:
- `AddIntervals()` method for easy interval creation with automatic repeat structure
- `AddRepeat()` method for custom repeat patterns with child steps
- Proper FIT file generation with parent repeat steps, child steps, and completion steps

**Comprehensive Target Support**: Full support for all Garmin target types including zones and custom ranges:
- Heart Rate zones (1-5) and custom BPM ranges (150-170)
- Speed zones (1-5) and custom speed ranges  
- Power zones (1-5) and custom wattage ranges
- Cadence custom ranges

**Enhanced Builder Methods**: Flexible warm-up and cool-down methods that accept target types:
```csharp
.WarmUp(15, 1, TargetType.Power)   // Power-based warm-up for cycling
.CoolDown(10, 1, TargetType.HeartRate)  // HR-based cool-down
```

**Pre-built Example Workouts**: Ready-to-use workout templates using repeat structures:
- `CreateIntervalWorkoutModel()` - 5x400m track intervals with proper repeat structure
- `CreateCyclingWorkoutModel()` - Power-based cycling intervals with 3x Build/Recovery pattern
- `CreateTempoRunModel()` - 20-minute tempo run

## Implementation Details

The library uses proper Garmin FIT SDK repeat patterns:
- **Repeat Steps**: Parent steps with `RepeatUntilStepsCmplt` duration type
- **Child Steps**: Interval and recovery steps contained within repeat structure  
- **Completion Steps**: Define how many times to repeat the pattern

This approach is more efficient and follows Garmin's recommended practices compared to manually creating individual interval steps.

## Project Structure

The solution file has been moved to the `src/` folder for better organization, with all projects properly referenced.

## Documentation

The README includes comprehensive examples covering:
- Basic workout patterns (warm up, main set, cool down) using `AddTimeStep`
- Interval workouts using repeat structures with explicit option objects
- Fartlek workouts with mixed interval patterns
- Custom repeat patterns and advanced usage
- Complete API documentation with real-world examples

## Testing

The library includes comprehensive test coverage with 23 unit tests covering:
- Model functionality and validation
- Fluent builder pattern behavior including new repeat methods
- File generation capabilities with repeat structure support
- All example workout scenarios using repeat patterns
- Custom target range functionality
- Edge cases and error handling

All tests pass and the library builds without warnings on .NET 8.

Fixes #1.
